Expand the readme with some architecture ideas

:stars: add an action that can update the props of a component

components that have the `editable` prop are wrapped by the
<EditableContent> container.
<EditableContent> is a connected component and merges an
`updateProps` dispatching function to its child.
The child can call updateProps with an object that can update its own
props. `updateProps` updates the global state (`layout`) with these
new properties and triggers a re-render through redux.
:wrench: connect the store to the container

:star2: example of a component with an `editable` prop

The `EditableDiv` component is an example of an editable component that
might live in one our generic component suites.

If rendered with `editable=true`, you can click on this component to
edit its text. On text input, the store is updated with the new props

:palm_tree: store the dependency graph in the store

:star: an `UpdateDependants` container

`UpdateDpendants` copies the child component and passes in a connected
`updateDependants` dispatching function that the presentational or
widget control can use when it wants to signify that its state has
updated and that its dependent components should use its new props to
update their values via the `/update-components` POST request

:wrench: keep the request queue in the store

(well need this in a subsequent commit)

:wrench: cache a copy of the layout paths to the components in the store

(well need this in a subsequent commit)

:fireworks: recursive updateDependants action

this function gets called when a component updates and dispatches
`updateDependants`.
this action:
- looks at the components dependants
- makes POSTs to /update-component for each of the components
dependants with all of the necessary dependencies
- updates each of the dependants with the new values from the
response of the /update-component POST
- recursively continues, dispatching to `updateDependants` with each of
those dependendants dependants

consider: A depends on B which depends on C
when C changes, it dispatches `updateDependants` to update the value of
B. on the response of that POST, B updates and makes a dispatch to
update A with Bs new values

prevent ConfirmDialog from firing multiple alerts at once

ConfirmDialog wasnt idempotent - if it was rendered multiple times in
a row with `display: true`, multiple confirm modals would be fired.

This didnt happen before in `dash-renderer` but it seems like it is
now with the `devtools` updates. Regardless of `dash-renderer`s
behaviour, this refactoring makes the component less brittle to its
parents logic.

This commit also simplifies the logic by making it stateless and
removing the `setProps` check now that `setProps` is always defined.

white_check_mark: every month has at least 28

standardize stateful component logic & style

certain components dont report their user-triggered values until a
certain user-trigger action. For example:
- `dcc.Input` may not report `value` on every keypress, only on enter
or blue (`debounce=true`)
- `dcc.Slider` may not report its value on `drag`, only on mouse up
(`updatemode=mouseup`)
- `dcc.DatePickerRange` may not report its value until both dates are
updated (`updatemode=bothdates`)

For these components, unify the data lifecycle:
1. Copy props to state on initialization
2. Copy props to state on component update (value could update from
`this.setProps` or from an output callback targeting `value`)
3. Use `{value} = this.state` in render
4. Use `this.setState` if the updatemode is local, otherwise use
`this.setProps`

simplify `Interval` with `setProps` & don't keep the timer running

Previously, if a callback told the `Interval` to stop (by setting
`max_intervals` to `0` or setting `disabled` to true), the timer would
keep running in the background and it just wouldnt report its value.

This had a couple of issues:
- There mightve been a performance hit (probably not large, but its
certainly unnecessary)
- If a callback told the timer to start _again_, then `n_intervals`
mightve been reported in the middle of an interval sequence (since the
interval was running). For example, consider the following scenario:
1. Interval updates very 5 seconds
2. A stop button sets `max_intervals` to `0`
3. (The interval continues to run in the background)
4. Another start button sets `max_intervals` to `-1`. The interval
was 4 seconds through its sequence so it reports its value in 1 second
and then again in 5 seconds. Rather than just at 5 seconds.

This uneven update upon re-start ends up feeling pretty glitchy.

feat: disable cookie/localstorage access under restricted sandboxes (#729)

When dash is embedded into an iframe with a sandbox attribute that only has allow-scripts, cookie/localstorage access is disabled and dash-core-components fails to load. As such, we need to restrict our cookie/localstorage usage by disabling functionality.

This patch moves the disabled functionality to a place where it doesn't get autoloaded regardless of usage, allowing dash-core-components to load in very restricted iframes.

feat: disable cookie access under restricted sandboxes (#677)

* feat: disable cookie access under restricted sandboxes

When dash is embedded into an iframe with a sandbox attribute that only has allow-scripts, cookie access is disabled and dash-table fails to load. As such, we need to restrict our cookie usage by disabling functionality.

This patch removes the disabled functionality in a graceful manner, allowing dash-table to load in very restricted iframes.

login view for at the end of an oauth flow

save the oauth token as a cookie

authorization endpoints

- Check if the viewer has access with the `oauth_token` contained in
the cookie
- If the viewer has access, then save an access code as a cookie
- When the viewer revists, the access code is compared with the access
code thats saved in memory as part of the app
- If the access codes dont match, then access is checked through the
oauth token and reset
- The access tokens expire after 5 minutes (configurable)

move class based config to a dict-based config

The class-based config was causing a few issues:
- It was being shared across instances of dash! This was a surprise to
me. Check this out:
```
In [1]: class Dash(object):
   ...:     def __init__(self):
   ...:         pass
   ...:     class config:
   ...:         b = 3
   ...:

In [2]: d1 = Dash()

In [3]: d1.config.b = 10

In [4]: d2 = Dash()

In [4]: d2.config.b = 15

In [5]: d1.config.b
Out[5]: 15

In [6]: d2.config.b
Out[6]: 15
```
- A dict-based config is just much better to deal with: you can
`print(app.config)` to see all of the values and defaults and you can
call dict methods like `update` on it.
- For backwards compatibility, `config` is a `AttributeDict` which
allows assignment through `__setattr__` (i.e. dot assignment), which
is how the previous config worked
- This also corrects the spelling correction to
`supress_callback_exceptions` but falls back to the original mispelled
version if the new version doesnt exist yet (for backwards
compatibility)

fix initialization routines

in initialization, we need to update all of the leaf inputs. sometimes,
there are leaf inputs with overlapping outputs. previously, we would
trigger an update for each input, which would then trigger an update
for each of its outputs. now, we skip triggering updates to outputs if
they have already been covered by a separate input.

The badges give a great quick visual overview of the Dash project.

simplify error overlay

In the previous version, we:
1. wrapped the output component with an overlay. This could cause flow
issues by introducing new markup on the page (e.g. wrapping a div with
a button).
2. Disabled the input components

This commit simplifies the logic and just displays the previous state
of the component, removes the overlay, and removes the disabled
elements.

Now, the markup on the page wont change when a front-end error happens
which makes it more similar to how the app changes when backend errors
occur.

Refactor Reloader component to work as a continuously mounted component

Some change to `dash-renderer` within the last 2 months (I cant
actually find which one) caused the `<Reloader/>` to stay mounted
rather than re-mount on soft reload. The previous logic would only
continue the reload checks on mount.

This commit enables the component to continue its reloading checks if
the component stays mounted. It also simplifies the logic a bit:
- I had a hard time keeping track of when `hash` was getting updated in
`state`. So, I simplified the logic to just compare the current request
against the previous request. The entire request is held in state
rather than unpacking `packages` & `hash`
- Requests are not triggered if a reload request is already in
progress. On my machine, reloading the python code can take like 10
seconds which was causing several requests to pile up and then all
subsequently update at once.
